  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Documenting transaction details\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Training staff on detection methods\n- Establishing compliance monitoring procedures\n\n4. Legal regulations\n- Complying with Bank Secrecy Act\n- Following Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering standards\n\n5. Record-keeping obligations\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Preserving customer identification documents\n- Storing financial records for specified periods\n\n6. Risk assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers\n- Conducting periodic risk evaluations\n- Implementing enhanced due diligence\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal prosecution.",
